It‚Äôs international women‚Äôs day and in Russian culture, this is a HUGE holiday! This is something I‚Äôve been celebrating since I was a kid and was really surprised that it‚Äôs only been recently implemented worldwide like this! In Russia, women get the day off and we receive flowers from family, friends, and loved ones. It‚Äôs a day we celebrate each other! Growing up, I remember waking up and enjoying some sort of cake or Russian pancakes with the table covered in beautiful bouquets of flowers. 

It‚Äôs a beautiful day and I‚Äôm glad it‚Äôs become as big as it has been!

I‚Äôve always been taught to be a tough female. I look to my mom A LOT and the older I become, the more I‚Äôm like her. I stand up for myself, I don‚Äôt take shit from ANYONE, I respect myself, and most importantly, I‚Äôm independent.

I don‚Äôt rely on anyone. I‚Äôve worked for everything I have. My parents are hard workers but since I‚Äôve been young, they‚Äôve always taught me to go and get the shit I want. And that‚Äôs exactly what I‚Äôm doing. I get down on myself a ton, but I‚Äôm EXACTLY where I want to be.

I‚Äôm glad to say that I‚Äôm confident, independent, and know how to stand up for myself. These are all SUCH important traits for us women to have! Listen to some Cardi B and freaking KNOW YOUR WORTH.

Respect yourself. Respect your body. Respect OTHERS.

Let‚Äôs bring each other up. Let‚Äôs stop putting other women down. I mean come on! It‚Äôs 2021. We are suchhhh badasses and we need to empower each other. Celebrate success and let‚Äôs work on encouraging ourselves to be the best versions of ourselves!

This is me kicking the past self, thoughts, demons, worries & concerns to the curb - 
‚Äã
Some of the most vulnerable states & lessons are sincerely taking time to realize you can free yourself from the pain of the past and there are great ways to face your demons.
‚Äã
‚ÄãWith the illumination inside of me and forgiveness inside of me, I have been able to face the craziest - painful and hurtful side of me - with grace & love - It hasn't been and wasn't easy, but once it was actually nailed down to see once and for all - the main objective has been to allow nothing but light to shine through awareness and understanding - I have become more aware of my unconscious actions and will never be a victim to them ever again.
‚Äã
‚ÄãWe all will or have faced circumstances such as these - but we don't want to talk about it because it might trigger something inside of you - it might bring you back to that scary, worried or fearful place, yet please believe me when I say, you will not know when they will reveal themselves, yet you will know how to respond and react because you know exactly what you are facing now!
‚Äã
‚ÄãYou were destined to live an abundant life - just as I am - just as your neighbor is - In order to move on, to be in forward motion, in conjunction to face the negative/demons in your life - which really is just a term for dealing with the repressed or unconscious aspects of your personality - we need to know that everything you desire lies on the other side of facing your demons!
‚Äã
‚ÄãAfter deep connection with Brendon Burchard's "The Motivation Manifesto" I'm stunned in my walk of facing my demons to be reminded that our internal demons poison us with worry and fear whenever we might be vulnerable, stunting our growth and vitality. Our destiny is decided by how well we know our demons of doubt and delay. How well we defend against them and how many battles we win against them each day of our lives.
‚Äã
‚Äã‚ÄãThrough Christ giving me my strength, I happily recognize these parts of my life and don't allow the past to be drawn into the future unless we make peace with it.
‚Äã

B R E A T H  W O R K O U T

Feeling the need to breathe deeply lately?
-
Try this breath workout.  Expand the belly during inhalation and relax the belly during exhalation.  Let your shoulders drop and jaw relax as you exhale.
-
When you feel angry or anxious breathing can become shallow.  This results in oxygen intake diminishing and muscle tension increasing.  Prolonge your exhalation as this promotes the relaxation response.  This expels the stress and tension from your system and brings you back into the present. 
-
Try this workout:
*Mentally count to 5 for the inhale
*count to 2 as you hold your breath
*count to 8 for the exhale
(15 seconds total for each breath x 4 rounds for a 1 minute breath workout)
-
Practice this when you feel tense or down.  This will help to slow your heart rate, calm your thoughts and find inner stillness in the moment.
-
Give it a try and comment below how you enjoyed this workout! üå¨

Back in the garage! It was a whopping 70 degrees today! I‚Äôm looking forward to the next few days of warmer temps! ‚òÄÔ∏è 

Today was all about Glutes/Hamstrings. I‚Äôve been having an issue with trigger finger on my right hand that‚Äôs affecting my ring finger, so I bought these @harbingerfitness lifting hooks. They saved me today for DL. I was even able to add weight which I haven‚Äôt done in so long! Definitely check them out if your grip is holding you back. 

I haven‚Äôt recorded myself in a bit. I can definitely tell it might be time to lean out some with summer coming up. Looking forward to some slow, steady progress to leaning out. I love the foods! So if that means increasing cardio to get my TDEE back up again that‚Äôs what I‚Äôll be doing. I‚Äôm gonna try to cut at 2000-2100 with adding in extra cardio over the next few weeks. If I don‚Äôt see any progress then I‚Äôll drop my calories to 1900-2000 while still doing the extra cardio. I‚Äôll throw in one untracked meal on the weekends. Cardio will be a mix of walking/interval training. 2-3 miles on the treadmill. I‚Äôll still lift 4 days a week with a full body thrown in the 5th and 6th day. Going back to only one rest day a week. I‚Äôll try to get some before photos taken this weekend so I can share my progress. Mostly I‚Äôll need them for myself. üòÇ I will say I for sure have gained some muscle, especially in the butt and thighs. Eating definitely helped with that! üòõ

EMOTIONAL EATING

I have struggled with emotional eating for YEARS. It makes sense, right? You‚Äôre upset, feeling down, out of control, why not turn towards food? Food gives you control, it triggers your endorphins, it satisfies. 

I would constantly turn to sweets when I had a rough day at work, if I was tired to perk me up, and when I just wanted comfort. It got to the point where I‚Äôd hide food wrappers from my parents or boyfriend because I felt so ashamed. I‚Äôd lie and say that I was starving,  when I just ate, so I could eat a second meal out with friends. I felt so fearful of judgement.

But at the end of the day, what I thought had given me control, really left me out of control all together. 

Now that I practice macro tracking, or flexible dieting, I can allow myself little treats when I want while still reaching my personal goals. I can truly have chocolate everyday, or a bagel and oatmeal in the same day. And with that freedom, that is the ULTIMATE CONTROL I was looking for all along. 

If you struggle with this too, know you‚Äôre not alone and I‚Äôm always here if you need support ‚ù§Ô∏è

‚Å£Ever wonder when you should stretch?‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Before or after your workout?‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Swipe or keep reading to find out!‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Static stretching is holding a stretch for 10-30 seconds ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Static stretching should occur after the strength training workout when the muscles temperature is increased, which can enhance range of motion (ROM)‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Static stretching can occur as a separate session on its own. However, in this case you still want to warm up the muscles to increase the muscle temperature ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Dynamic stretching can occur before the exercise session. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Dynamic stretches are movements that are more specific to the exercise about to be performed. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Dynamic stretches can help warm up the body for exercise. ‚†Ä

What‚Äôs the right weight for you?‚öñÔ∏è

Here‚Äôs how you figure it out and how to stop stressing over the perfect number, because there is no such thing.

First you should learn your body and fully understand your hunger cues.

Learn to eat in a way that makes you feel good.

Does that mean you track your food or you eat intuitively?

Either, pick the one that‚Äôs right for you.

Tracking is a great tool and it will definitely help you achieve your goals.

Intuitive eating meaning- your diet consists of Whole Foods and the other delicious foods out there but in a way that‚Äôs not going to make you feel horrible. Like tracking but not tracking.

When you allow your body to enjoy the foods that it‚Äôs eating, living more of a carefree lifestyle and providing it with the proper nutrients, you will find that your weight is going to land where it should.

I believe that we are all built differently and that we all are meant to have a weight range.

I don‚Äôt like to put down a certain number for when it comes to weight loss because we are not a specific number.

Our weight is always fluctuating for many reasons such as‚Ä¶.üëáüèºüëáüèº

üí™üèºMuscle mass.
üò©Menstruating.
üçüDiet is high in Sodium.
ü•µStress.
üôÖüèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èWeighing at the wrong time of day.

There are many factors that play into weight loss. So as you see, when you learn to balance out your lifestyle, your body listens. It will respond when it recognizes that it‚Äôs being cared for with love.

Also, if you are on a weight loss journey, having a weight loss goal is perfectly okay! Just remember that the goal is to learn how to care for your body the proper way and the rest will follow.

Can we stop normalizing the word ‚Äúcant.‚Äù Besides your ex, that has to be the most toxic thing you can do. Don‚Äôt allow that word in your arsenal. If you normalize ‚Äúwell I can‚Äôt‚Äù you‚Äôre just going to apply that to every single thing you try to do. I remember first trying to do muscle ups, I was so bad at them. I could barely do pull ups let alone a muscle up. After every training session I would attempt a couple. I would fail over and over again. I just couldn‚Äôt pull it together. It was very frustrating to the point where I almost said ‚Äúfuck this‚Äù and gave up. After the billionth time, I somehow managed to chicken wing my way up and complete 1!! After countless times of failing, I finally managed to get one. I don‚Äôt even know how long it took to string a couple together in a row. I just kept at it. The road to accomplishing anything is never straight and perfect. Its going to be tough especially when seeing other people get it before you do. Don‚Äôt let that bring you down and just stick to the game plan. Don‚Äôt let failing deter you from your goals. Failing is apart of life. It‚Äôs the most human thing you can do. Once you acknowledge that, the word ‚Äúcan‚Äôt‚Äù  won‚Äôt be part of your vocabulary anymore.

Yesterday was a body weight workout with time under tension. Slowing everything down and really thinking about the movement you‚Äôre performing is where neuromuscular connection comes into play. This is when your muscle fibers connect with motor neurons. Think about it like this: have you experience a sensation where you pick up on a sound, and it becomes impossible to hear anything else? Or once you see a shape in the cloud above you, your eyes are able to see it again? Now apply that to your body. Let‚Äôs say you were performing a bodyweight squat, and you really focus on hinging your hips backwards and feeling the impact it has on your quads, glutes, and reduce pain in your knees. When you actively focus on the lengthening and contracting of your muscles, balance, posture, & controlling the movement you reduce your risk for injury, increase your strength, and muscle growth. #FitWithBritt ‚Ä¢‚Ä¢I do not own the rights to this music‚Ä¢‚Ä¢

We love fiber, but unfortunately, most people don‚Äôt eat enough of it.

The RDA (recommended daily amount), according to the Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics is 25 grams for women and 38 grams for men OR 14 grams per 1,000 calories consumed.

The majority of new clients come to me eating less than that on a consistent basis. How much is right for you will vary, however, 25 grams (for women) is a good number to aim for. If you‚Äôre super low on fiber to start, make sure you SLOWLY increase your intake over time. You also need to make sure you‚Äôre staying consistent with your intake on a daily basis (30 grams one day and 4 grams the next isn‚Äôt going to cut it).

Fiber is not only important for digestion, but it also increases satiety (keeps you full for longer) and helps regulate blood sugar and blood cholesterol (among many other things). My top 6 (because I couldn‚Äôt pick just 5) favorite sources of fiber include old fashioned oats, ground flaxseed, raspberries, avocado, chickpea pasta, and salad bowls packed with veggies and allll the micros like this one from @dailycleanfoodanddrink pictured here üòã

And just like that its been a year (and a few days üòÇ) since I started running with my coach, @billbrumbachocr . The timing of it all was somewhat serendipitous - I had been wanting to work on my running for quite some time and I finally got my shit together and started in March 2020 - right before the world shut down. Previously I always had trouble running more than 2-3 miles because my knees would always hurt. I never paid attention to my heart rate. And I always had such a hard time recovering from long runs. The world was still fairly normal the first week I did Bill's programming and I would head down to Sports and Wellness to use their treadmills to get my runs done. Fast forward two weeks, the world basically shut down and I had to move my runs outside. Man oh man. What a year it has been. All of these benchmarks I have accomplished within this past year - with my most recent PR - my 1 mile from last Tuesday. I never thought I could run that fast much less run in the cold. It's one thing running on a treadmill, it's a whole other beast getting out and propelling yourself to run FAST on the road and the trials. Throughout the year I have seen and been through so much on my runs. I've explored around the city and have so much more to explore! I have found something that is super sustainable for my body - I can run 3 hours one day and have recovered enough to run 90 minutes the next day. My knees don't hurt after 2-3 miles. I am so incredibly thankful that I have the coach that I do. Bill - you are awesome. You are an amazing coach and an amazing friend and I can't wait to see what I can accomplish with your guidance over this next year!

Why waste time proving over and over how great you are, when you could be getting better? Why hide deficiencies instead of overcoming them? Happy Tuesday! 

How‚Äôs your day going? 

For today‚Äôs workout, I did some cardio on my spin bike then finished my workout off with some glute exercises. One of the moves I did was bridges. This move always works your hamstrings as well. If you want to add more resistance, you can add on weights while doing them. 

Tips: 
1. Lay flat on your back and keep your core engaged. 
2. Lift off the ground and hold for 2 seconds and bring it back down. 
3. When you bring your hips up, make sure you squeeze your glutes.

caption:
Back with another dirty workout in the pain cave gym!!!

‚òòÔ∏èI love drop sets because they allow you to burn out a muscle group and get a ton of reps in a short amount of time. 

‚òòÔ∏èA drop set is what it sounds like- you literally drop weight off and immediately go into the next set up reps. For example, I started with 8 heavy hip thrusts, dropped a plate and went immediately into 10 reps, dropped the weight, and finished with 12 body weight reps. All of these sets will finish with body weight reps!

‚òòÔ∏è The last round is a combo move where you don‚Äôt put the bar down until you finish all the exercises- so go directly into each exercise after you finish 5 reps! The exercises should flow into one another

‚òòÔ∏è I added 5 minutes of steady biking before each new circuit to keep my heart rate high but you can always do some jump roping, jumping jacks, etc to keep your heart rate high!

‚òòÔ∏è screenshot the end or bookmark this workout to save! It took me about an hour!!!

Over the next few days I will be sharing 5 different movements for de-stressing your body. Particularly for those of you who have been working long hours at home during the pandemic. 
-
Today is day 2 - The Cat/Cow
-
-
This video offers a quick tutorial on how to keep mobility throughout your body by flexing and extending the spine. 
-
Most of us, who work from home, spend countless hours haunching over a computer screen. This can cause unnecessary strain, and even damage, to our bodies. 
-
Take breaks through the work day to: walk, move, stretch, squat, lunge, rotate, reach, flex, and what-the-f-ever-else; JUST GET UP and MOVE! 
-
A great trick is to set a timer for every 2 hours; try to complete 3-5 stretches before you go back to work. Also, It is a good habit to stand as much as possible while working at a computer; there are tons of standing desk options available. 

-
Lastly, be mindful with core stacking, breathing, bracing, and tension. Check all the boxes and you‚Äôll notice you won‚Äôt feel as stiff and achy anymore. 
-
Move Better ‚Ä¢ Feel Better ‚Ä¢ Live Better

first three pics were taken 3/9, which is about 5 weeks since I decided to get back on track with my nutrition, focus on protein intake and be in a caloric deficit (using @avatarnutrition ), and prioritize sleep. the last picture was taken 2/1. They are real, unfiltered and not photoshopped. I‚Äôm down 8 pounds, feeling extremely strong, and proud of my commitment to my goals. I didn‚Äôt change any workout habits and continued to lift heavy, primarily with kettlebells. and no, I didn‚Äôt do 2 hours of cardio a day ü§™

am I a better person because I lost weight? no. am I happier because I lost weight? in some aspects- I‚Äôm so proud I am committing to myself and my hard work is paying off, sure. But in many ways I‚Äôm not, and not because of this body journey, but because life throws your curveballs and stressors. But that‚Äôs life. 

I‚Äôm not posting this to get self validation, or to have people tell me how great I look, but to remind you life is hard sometimes. and that‚Äôs ok. I know I‚Äôm able to keep going because I‚Äôm a strong fucking woman. I‚Äôm dedicated. I give everything my all. I know who i am and I‚Äôm proud of that person.

I still have goals in regards to my body composition, which I plan to achieve over the next few months, with time. No fad diets, still enjoying dinners out, casual glasses of wine and cocktails. I‚Äôll get there with discipline, but I‚Äôm doing so in a healthy and sustainable manner. I‚Äôm proud of myself. And I love myself. And sometimes that‚Äôs all you need ‚ù§Ô∏è

Insights into athleticism and #MakeLittAthleticAgain: multiplanar power.

If you've been watching, you've seen me add a load of lateral movements into my training in the last few weeks. Most of them have been strength based, working to increase the ability to produce forces in the frontal and transverse planes. 

With the goal of being more athletic approaching more rapidly then I thought, I've begun to add more multiplanar power work. Power is a byproduct of force and velocity, so the goal is to produce force quickly, and do so in multiple planes of motion.

I incorporated this Medball slam into my training the other day as part of fitting within that goal: moving through both the frontal and transverse planes (think lateral and rotational), and moving at lighter loads that can be moved quickly. The reactive/rebounding component was added for my pure enjoyment.

I almost always say three time's a charm when we practice deep asanas. üí´

The first time is getting a feel for what we're about to do, the entrance, the engagement, the exit. The second time, less assisted, I want to make sure they're capable, focused and in control. The third time, I'm on standby. They do what they can and I'm ready in arms reach.

Arching your back during a bench press can help reduce the risk of injury. 

It puts your shoulder joints into a much more favourable position. 

It reduces issues of shoulder impingement.

It allows you to have more range of motion and simply helps you to distribution that load more effectively.

But what I kept experiencing myself and seeing in others through the years is injury after injury. I was tired of dealing with it myself through the years but more so, watching others deal with it as well. Does it mean injury can‚Äôt occur with other sports or training. Absolutely not. Any type of training or sports leaves you open to injury. BUT some more the others. I‚Äôve learned to slow things down a bit and honestly, happier, less stress on my body and feel healthier then ever. Change is scary but needed sometimes. Then as time went on, I stopped going. I never understood why? 

I always thought about dancing over the years, but rarely did anything about it. 

I‚Äôd break out a freestyle flow once in a while if I was home alone and felt safe. 

So not much at all. 

The thought of posting a video of myself dancing  absolutely terrifies me. 

Posting THIS video is a big deal to me. I‚Äôm so glad I listened to that little voice in my head over the years that told me to never give up on dancing. It‚Äôs so FUN!!!

I learned this past year that I need creative and flowing outlets in my life and dancing allows me to do it all. 

I can‚Äôt wait to post more about my dancing and how I hope to empower women to step outside of her comfort zone! 

Yes it‚Äôs scary! Terrifying. I know the feeling. 

Take a few deep breaths and ask yourself, are my fears valid? 

The answer is NO! 

If more women continue to support one another, the world could be a much kinder, loving place. 

BE YOU. FEEL YOU. LOVE YOU. 

Oh yes... and don‚Äôt forget to SMILE üòÅ!

Be intentional in creating the physical foundation of the pose and be up to something bigger than yourself.

‚ÄúWhat is the best training split?‚Äù

Answer - There is no one best training split.

The best training split for YOU is probably going to be different than the best training split for me, your friend, your significant other, etc..

Just because somebody else is seeing results while following a certain training split doesn‚Äôt mean you have to follow that same split to see results yourself.

You can have success training 2-3 days per week, 4-5 days per week, OR 6 days per week. You can have success training for 45 minutes at a time OR 1-2 hours at a time. See a pattern here?

The most important thing is that you are following a program YOU can adhere to - one that works for your body, fits your lifestyle, and one you enjoy.

With an efficiently programmed training plan, you CAN be successful with what best fits your schedule and lifestyle. I am proof. My clients are proof. Even @frommy20 is proof ü§≠üòâ There are so many ways to make progress and the best way is going to be doing things that work best for you. Make your training split fit your lifestyle, make it enjoyable, and stay consistent. THAT is what really matters.

If you need help figuring out what the best training split is for you, I can help you out. 1:1 coaching available via the link in my bio.

Here are some main key takeaways from the workshop we went over!

1Ô∏è‚É£Back pain is multi factorial and can be influenced by a multitude of different factors.

2Ô∏è‚É£MRIs/Imaging aren‚Äôt always needed to detect the cause of low back pain. ‚ÄúAbnormalities‚Äù that show up on imaging are actually extremely common in asymptomatic (people without pain) and don‚Äôt predict how much pain one experiences.

3Ô∏è‚É£Movement is medicine! If flare ups do occur, find pain free movements and keep moving!

4Ô∏è‚É£Pain with exercise and movement doesn‚Äôt mean you are doing damage or harm. Pain with movement reflects how sensitive certain structures are, not how damaged you are. Utilizing movement and graded exposure, we can desensitize these uncomfortable positions over time!

5Ô∏è‚É£The back is extremely robust, resilient, and strong! üí™üèº It‚Äôs made to bend, rotate, and can adapt if we expose it to an environment and loads in a graded manner!

Becoming a coach with Beachbody has probably been the best decision I have made.

Growing up I always was into sports and had that community type of feeling. We cheered each other on we had goals to look forward to!

Fast forward to college; I was majoring in nursing, and had that support group. And then I moved to NC. All I did was go to work, eat and sleep. I had nothing to look forward to. I started binging on Netflix and stress eating. I. Was. Miserable.

Fast forward to June of 2018 I saw my now coach on my discovery page and realized I wanted to do whatever she was doing.

She got in shape. Looked happy. Had an amazing community of friends...AND was a nurse. I reached out to her.

 I craved the support each woman gave each other! It wasn‚Äôt all about me...it was a we effort.

We all clapped for each other‚Äôs success.

I watched teachers, nurses, doctors, lawyers all leave their full time jobs for coaching.

It gives me chills.

If you are looking for a group to empower you to do your absolute best, this is for you!

You are never alone. You are never stuck. We are here for you!

caption: This strong woman making her mark on the world is part of all the strong women who came before her and led the way. Ladies..Lost your period from working out? Listen up.

What is the female athlete triad?

Three interrelated factors including energy availability, menstrual function and bone mineral density 

When energy availability is low (in the case of a low number of calories taken in and high amount of energy expended) females can develop menstrual irregularities. 

Prolonged periods of low energy availability along with lack of mensuration will then eventually impact bone mineral density of a female athlete 

Protein, calcium and vitamin D all play a pivotal role in keeping BMD high. 

As bones decline in structure and deteriorate there becomes and even bigger risk for fractures.. specifically for athletes stress fractures 

What can you do? 

1. First, consult with your doctor. If they tell you this is normal, be skeptical 
2. Make sure you are consuming adequate calories to suite your personal needs 
3. Consume protein, ideally from lean sources such as poultry, low fat dairy, fish, lean beef, lentils etc

Pay attention to signs 

1. Sleep quality
2. Overall energy/mood 
3. Recovery from training

Hello friends!! Do you struggle to recovery effectively after your workouts? Do you find that your body feels sore and stiff for DAYS after an intense lift? Here are a few things that have aided me in my muscle recovery process:
.
üå∑GLUTAMINE- a free form amino acid abundantly found in the body that will aid in rebuilding muscles post workout and is an incredible supplement to support immunity and intestinal health. 
üå∑COLLAGEN- supplementing collagen will aid in the reparation of muscle fibers, and promotes / supports strong and flexible tendons and ligaments. 
üå∑FOAM ROLLING & STATIC STRETCH- foam rolling can help in breaking up lactic acids within the muscles, relieve tightness & soreness, reduce inflammation as well as increase range of motion. The same goes for your post workout static stretches. 
üå∑ADEQUATE SLEEP & REST- getting a sufficient amount of sleep & rest allows for an increase of exercise performance, conservation of energy, and will allow for your body to restore and repair itself meaning more productive workouts. 
üå∑H2O- cliche but so essential. Staying hydrated allows your body to properly transport nutrients throughout your body and remove harmful toxins that could be detrimental to your health. Especially if you‚Äôre taking preworkout or supplementing creatine as a tool to build muscle, it is ESSENTIAL that you‚Äôre keeping your body hydrated. Drinking plenty of water also increases energy production and aids in fatigue relief making it easier to stay consistent with your workouts. 
.
As I‚Äôm consistently back in the swing of things with my fitness goals, my body is still getting acclimated to the physical stressors of my training split. Meaning I‚Äôve been very sore! I‚Äôve talked to a few friends and dabbled around and these are the most common things that seem to help the most in proper recovery. I hope this was helpful & you‚Äôre smashing your gym goals! üíû

Today I feel beyond blessed to have not one, not two, but THREE best friends who are all women. They‚Äôre all so unique, yet we all have things in common with each other. The theme this year is "Choose to Challenge" which is the absolute perfect theme for me this year. I just finished my 45 day challenge with @f45_training_westparkridge
and couldn't be happier with my results!

I have always worked out on the reg and watched what I ate. Once gyms opened back up after COVID I got right back to it. I was killing myself every day but wasn't seeing any results! I wondered why. Once they told us about the 45 day challenge I knew it was something I needed to participate in. I have never been one for fad diets or anything like that. Eating right is a lifestyle choice and something I have always stuck with. I have never cut out any food groups (which you can read about in one of my blog posts) you need to make sure you're eating from each and every one just in moderation! I know what works best for me and which foods I should stay clear from. You need to learn your body and what works for you. For some reason the way I use to eat was no longer working for me. They say your body changes every 7 years so I guess my time was up! It was time to start recording my food intake and really pay attention to calories and micronutrients which I have never done before.

I am currently down 6.6 lbs (which isn't much for 45 days but it's a good start).
Lost 2 inches in my waist.
Lost 2 1/2 inches in my hips.
Lost 1 inch in my arms.
Lost 1/2 inch in my chest and thighs.

I can see the changes in my body which makes me want to push myself even more.

This picture was taken about half way through the challenge and before I had to take 10 days off due to testing positive for COVID. I felt defeated at that point. I was doing so good and thought I would end up back at square one with not working out for 10 days. Boy was I wrong! #iwd2021

What are you going to challenge yourself with this year?!

1. Lift up through the crown of your head, reach your fingertips forward and hinge your body up and back. Bring one leg up, out, in and down. Same leg 4x. Switch legs.

4. Scissor switches again. 6 sets. 
5. Keep the arms where the are, bend the knees in towards the chest, legs glued together and feet are flexed. Bend knees in, straighten legs out. 6x. 
6. Turn the legs out once again. Same exercise as #3 to finish off!

caption:
‚ú®MOVEMENT MONDAY‚ú®

Would like to start by saying Happy International Women‚Äôs Day to all the badass women-identifying people I know ü•∫ü§ç I am a better woman because of the people I have in my life, including the support of so many of you!

Today we‚Äôre going to quickly run down some of the common variations of deadlifts out there as I‚Äôve gotten many questions for clarification!

1Ô∏è‚É£RDLs/Romanian Deadlifts: often done with dumbbells and very similar to a traditional deadlift. The main difference being how far the chest comes over the feet as well as the fact that the weights do not touch the floor, but rather stop at about shin height. The knees are slightly bent, and the glutes/hips hinge backwards
2Ô∏è‚É£Stiff-Legged Deadlifts: very similar to the RDL with chest position and weights not touching the floor, but legs stay more straight (a SLIGHT bend is okay, but legs should be mostly straight)
3Ô∏è‚É£Barbell Deadlift: weight starts on the floor, and comes back to the floor between each rep (whether it be tap-and-go or resetting each time). You generally sit a little deeper in the starting position, with your legs bent a bit more, and your chest higher and further back

All of these seem quite similar and follow the same movement pattern, but they incorporate different fibres from different muscle groups and should be varied in your programs intentionally! 

As per usual, if you wanted to save this for your next deadlift day or to check up on your form, I would really appreciate your support ü§çü§çü§ç

I hope you all have the best start to your day!

Do your neck, back, shoulders feel tight all the time? What about persistent back pain or aching? Tension headaches? How you breathe could be a big component.

We take as many as 15,000 breaths or more per day. You better believe that how we do something fifteen THOUSAND times, day in and day out, will affect how we feel.

If you‚Äôre not breathing with your diaphragm, then you‚Äôre probably using your shoulder, upper chest, and neck muscles to drive each inhale. These are your ‚Äúaccessory breathing muscles,‚Äù which are supposed to help you breathe only when you‚Äôre respirating as hard as you can, like at the end of a sprint. They are not supposed to be breathing for you all the time. But persistent stress, poor movement variability, and lack of practice/awareness can lead to them taking over.

What happens when you use an accessory system as your primary way to breathe, 15,000 times, every day? It will start to feel tight, no matter how much stretching you do. Imagine squeezing your hand all day - it‚Äôs going to feel tight! 

And because it connects to your low back, under activity of the diaphragm will start to affect how the low back feels as well.

Breathing has gotten a lot of hype recently, and while not a miracle cure for everyone, it‚Äôs certainly a big piece we can‚Äôt ignore.

This International Women‚Äôs Day, I‚Äôd like to celebrate FEMALE RAGE aka the emotion that we‚Äôve been taught is off-limits to us because it makes us hard to control.

I think EVERY person deserves to be acknowledged and validated for their full range of feelings.

The more we shame people into hiding and judging their emotions, the less everyone feels authentic and worthy of connection.

The misogynists can call us ‚Äúextra‚Äù, ‚Äúdramatic‚Äù, ‚Äúfragile‚Äù, ‚Äúcrrrrrazy‚Äù, ‚Äúbitchy‚Äù, ‚Äúbossy‚Äù but that is their fears and insecurities trying to contain a women‚Äôs intuitive wisdom.

You‚Äôre not just another stereotypical angry women, you‚Äôre a human being feeling a valid emotion that is informing you that your boundary has been crossed in some way.

Ladies, acknowledge your anger, process it, and let it grow your wisdom. The more you suppress it, the more toxic it becomes. And the person getting hurt the most is...YOU.

While we all cheer on our fave women for their nurturing and kindness today, I am raising my glass to my gals and our entitlement to respect and healthy self-expression.

A woman‚Äôs tale.

These bodies enveloppes us.
These bodies the world sees.
Society judges us and says:
This body is too curvy, this body too skinny, this body holds too much muscle, this body,too much fat. 
Let‚Äôs cut her open and insert silicone here and remove fat here. Let‚Äôs tighten her intestines. Let‚Äôs inject her Gluteus. 
 
After all the adjustments we think to ourselves: the work is done and now I look better, surely the world will accept me: surely I am worthy now. 

But hold your horses not so fast; have you forgotten dear women?

Our faces are not spared of society‚Äôs scrutiny and they are next in line:

Her nose is too big and this girls lips are too thin. And this girl would look so much better with Keratin.  Her skin is too pale and her skin is too dark. Her hair should be lighter her cheeks should be fuller. Let‚Äôs tattoo her eyebrows and get rid of her wrinkles eliminate crow feet around the eyes
Botox them.
Her crow feet and wrinkles. Proof she and cried and smiled and laughed and lived. Let‚Äôs erase it all. Let‚Äôs eliminate her emotions any trace of a feeling 
Freeze her face in time. 

Perpetual messages of unworthyness. 
Perpetual messages that our inherent value is remaining frozen in time, a forever improving doll.

Good morning team. Happy Monday. We always say new week new opportunities all around us just gotta be willing to look and embrace. 

I wanted to talk a little today about hip abduction. I see regularly in the gym a over use of bands and abductions machines. Now I say this with absolutely no judgement. There was a time when we were told in order to build great Glutes we required bands and loads of abduction work. I‚Äôm here to tell you this couldn‚Äôt be further from the truth. Banding squats, hip thrusts and always taking a wide stance is not optimal for Glute growth. In fact research is now showing the Glute max is more efficiently trained in a narrow position. 

In order to build great Glutes we need to ficus predominately on the Glute max. This is the largest muscle. We target with compound movements. Squats, deadlifts, lunges, split squats. 

I talk to a lot of women and a large majority of them suffer from lower back pain, hip issues and Glutes they wish were bigger. Tons of abduction work is most definitely the culprit here. When we pull the work out of the targeted muscle which is much larger and put it into a much smaller one the body will respond and its not usually good. Sacrum, piriformis, hips all take the brunt here team. 

Here is a effective exercise to add at the end of a lower body workout. Light weight! 

A cable abduction 
2 sets 20 per side 
Rest 30 secs 

That‚Äôs it that‚Äôs all you need. Give these a shot teamüçë

Revolved hand to foot (aka ‚Äúdancing Shiva‚Äù) - Parivrtta Hasta Padangusthasana 

Shiva is known as the destroyer because he breaks things down for us so that even better things can come into place. The name ‚ÄúShiva‚Äù can be translated to mean the ‚Äúgood‚Äù or ‚Äúbenevolent one.‚Äù The destruction can occur in relation to any aspects of ourselves which does not serve us, such as certain parts of our ego or the obstacles that may get in our way of having happiness and contentment in our lives. 

One example of this can be when a relationship or a job ends, and we might see this as a TERRIBLE thing, but we later realize that it was for the best. As a counselor, I often help people through some very difficult break ups. At first, they are devastated, sad, and can see no ‚Äúlight‚Äù at the end of the tunnel. In the end, the clients often realize that they are finding even greater happiness following the ending of the relationship. They are finding greater self confidence and less anxiety because they often realize (later) that the relationship was not healthy overall. 

Yoga, as a practice, also helps us to break down old patterns and thoughts which no longer serve us to make room for even better behaviors and thoughts. Case in point, I have continued to find eating habits that are in my best interest. I continuously learn more about my body and which supplements and foods work the best for me.

Most of us, who work from home, spend countless hours haunching over a computer screen. This can cause unnecessary strain, and even damage, to our bodies. 
-
Take breaks through the work day to: walk, move, stretch, squat, lunge, rotate, reach, flex, and what-the-f-ever-else; JUST GET UP and MOVE! 
-
A great trick is to set a timer for every 2 hours; try to complete 3-5 stretches before you go back to work. Also, It is a good habit to stand as much as possible while working at a computer; there are tons of standing desk options available.

Mobility Monday

I love the overhead squat because of the overall demands it places on the body. 

Though it is very impressive to put up big numbers, I generally use the overhead squat more for mobility purposes. I have found that if I can comfortably get into an overhead squat, my entire body is generally feeling great! 

I messed around this morning with some close grip overhead squats to work on mobility. Notice that I didn‚Äôt add any weight! Mainly because each progression of narrowing the hands makes the movement more and more difficult.

I have always said that one should able to overhead squat more than they bench press! 

Try a broom stick or empty barbell first. Loading this movement is NOT necessary. Just getting into the position can be tricky!

If you try it out, tag me! ü§ô

A few years ago I made it my mission to change, support and strengthen women physically, mentally and emotionally not only in my personal life but also my career. It‚Äôs been the biggest game changer seeing women turn their lives around for themselves.

Today I only had about 30ish min to train so I thought to myself - ‚Äúwhat have I been neglecting lately?‚Äù Spending time with my parents? Yes. But also conventional deadlifts. So I opted for some German volume training. What is GVT?
Essentially, you perform an exercise (or two) for 10 sets of 10 repetitions. Usually a compound lift (squat, bench, deadlift etc)
Things to note:
‚ñ™Ô∏èthis is not necessarily for everyone and anyone. If you struggle with reoccurring injuries, joint pain, mobility issues...this might not be for you due to the high volume.
‚ñ™Ô∏èmake sure you have the movement pattern down and your form is solid. Yes I have to work on my deadlift still but I‚Äôd say that I move quite safely and am not putting spine or body in general at risk. 
‚ñ™Ô∏èpick a weight that you can do for 20reps roughly 60% of your 1RM. 
‚ñ™Ô∏èrest for about 60-90sec if you‚Äôre simply repeating one exercise for the 10 sets. 
‚ñ™Ô∏è MY TEMPO NEEDS WORK. It‚Äôs funny how when you‚Äôre doing the lift you feel like you‚Äôre going at a good pace but looking back at the video I‚Äôm like sis, hold the heck up. Control that  dang eccentric!!! 
Anywho this goes back to the whole, ‚Äúhey cutie, YOU DO NOtttt NEED TO OVERCOMPLICATE YOUR TRAINING!!!‚Äù Learn the basics, practice the basics, master the basics. And dont be afraid to enjoy the moments between the sets. Wheymen.

Cognitive Dissonance: the state of having inconsistent thoughts, beliefs, or attitudes, especially as relating to behavioral decisions and attitude change.

This theory was my FAVORITE in all of my communication courses in college because it plays such a big part in our lives.

Our brain craves consistency. You can‚Äôt say & believe one thing and then expect to act the opposite way.

You can‚Äôt constantly say ‚ÄúI‚Äôm not a morning person‚Äù and expect to try to create a new habit of waking up early. You can‚Äôt say ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt like the way healthy food tastes,‚Äù and then expect to change your eating habits. 

If you want to create new, healthier habits, you have to start thinking & showing up as the type of person who already has those habits.

So, start saying ‚ÄúI am a morning person,‚Äù if you want to start waking up earlier. If you want to start eating more nutrient dense foods & have a healthier relationship with food, start saying ‚ÄúI eat to fuel my body & don‚Äôt believe in ‚Äògood‚Äô or ‚Äòbad‚Äô foods.‚Äù

The easiest way to create the best version of yourself is to believe that you already are that person, and start showing up as her every single day. 

Let‚Äôs go get better today!

I‚Äôve never liked any variation of warrior pose, probably because it‚Äôs one of my weakest and I find my mind wandering every time I‚Äôm in it. Welcome to week 2 of March Mindfulness! This week is all about getting grounded in ourselves. To be grounded means to be rooted in the present moment, like a tree that stands firm in the middle of natural disaster. A sense of calm & peace while chaos surrounds it.

To be a tree is impossible, you‚Äôre human. But to learn from a tree holds value. We all have thoughts that burden us & make us feel like we‚Äôre running a million miles a minute, bouncing from one to the next, getting so lost in them that we forget to be present. But being able to stay rooted while the turmoil of your thoughts are swirling around you & not let it take you with it is powerful.

From that place, we can observe our thoughts rather than getting swept up in them. 

Anxious feeling is a natural part of being human & its not going to magically disappear. It‚Äôs challenging to navigate, thats why this week I wanted to focus on giving you a way to find your center & inner calm when theres a storm brewing ü§ç

caption:
So, you want to get ‚Äútoned‚Äù?‚Å£
‚Å£
Being ‚Äútoned‚Äù really just means that you have developed muscle and your body fat percentage is low enough that you can see that muscle. ‚Å£
‚Å£
The concept of being ‚Äútoned‚Äù was created specifically for women. It gives the impression of having defined muscles but definitely not toooo bulky and is used to sell specific products and programs that promise results. ‚Å£
‚Å£
The truth is that getting toned doesn‚Äôt require anything special, fancy or different but just time to focus on two different goals:‚Å£
‚Å£
1Ô∏è‚É£Phase 1: Building muscle requires eating at maintenance calories (or slightly above) and focusing on resistance training with progressive overload.‚Å£
‚Å£
2Ô∏è‚É£Phase 2: Fat loss to expose the muscle you just built and appear ‚Äútoned‚Äù by eating in a caloric deficit, possibly adding additional cardio, and continuing a progressive overload based program. ‚Å£
‚Å£
^this takes time, consistency and likely a few cycles through these phases! ‚Å£
‚Å£
I want women to be better than ‚Äútoned‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
We should be able to talk about our goals in an educated and accurate way rather than using terms created for females that don‚Äôt really make sense. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Next time someone asks you about your fitness goals, instead of saying you want to get ‚Äútoned‚Äù consider what it is you really want! Fat loss OR muscle buildingüí™üèª

‚ûñFLAT FEET?‚ûñ

No you don‚Äôt need any fancy shoes you need to strengthen up your feet! Try these 4 moves to strengthen the arch in your foot, and decrease foot pain that comes along with flat feet! 

On top of these 4 moves, make sure that when you train you go shoeless when possible to better strengthen your feet and receive stronger nerve signals from ground contact! Aka better muscle activation ‚úîÔ∏è 

1) Foot grabs- imagine your feet are hands and gather the ground with your foot creating the arch

2) Standing calf raises- lift up to your tips toes, hold, release to ground slowly 

3) Toes elevated, side rocks- keeping toes off the ground the entire time rock from the ankles side to side slowly, keeping legs/knees straight 

4) Arch trigger point- using a lacrosse ball, tennis ball, KB handle- anything you can find and dig into that arch to help release tension and lengthen. 

Try each move 12-15 reps for 3 rounds as a warmup before every training or cardio session! Remember your feet hold your entire body so here‚Äôs your reminder to show them some love and care ‚ú®ü§ç‚úîÔ∏è #flatfeet

My goal doesn‚Äôt always look like a marathon, but for this season it does, and I am so grateful for all the highs and lows it has brought. Most people don‚Äôt understand what this journey looks like, and that‚Äôs okay. It‚Äôs the reason why I choose to surround myself with people who have ran numerous marathons... which brings me to my next point. If you feel like you‚Äôre struggling to move forward in a certain area of your life, the best thing you can do (IMO) is hang around people who have already accomplished what you‚Äôre striving for üòä Looking to become financially free? Hangout with someone who was once in debt and now is financially abundant. Looking to make a career move? Hangout with someone who is currently successful in the industry you‚Äôre looking to switch to. Looking to better your physical health? Hangout with someone who has overcome the struggles you‚Äôre currently facing. Looking to run a marathon? Hangout with someone who has run several. Don‚Äôt be too proud to ask for help. Don‚Äôt be too proud to be in room full of people who know more than you. Ask questions. Take notes. Study these people and their daily habits. Note to my 15-year-old self. ‚ù§Ô∏è

You‚Äôre going to spend a lot of years trying to be liked, trying to fit in, and trying to be excepted in a culture and a world that is not your own. 

You will be hurt by a lot of people who you perceived to be friends. But one day, you‚Äôll wake up in your self worth and understand your definition of true friendship. 

You will understand that your strength frustrates them because it highlights their perceived weaknesses.

You will understand that your persistence frustrates them because it highlights their complacency.

You will understand that even though your heart is pure and that you are a kind person, some will always see you as competition and an enemy.

You will understand that your boundaries for self love will upset them and they will label you as angry, and unapproachable.

You will understand that dimming your shine does not help them shine brighter and that helping others shine makes your light even more vibrant.

You will step into you power. And use that power to help others like you step into theirs. 

And you will understand the quickest way to change the world is a make a friend that does not look like you.

Yes you can. Yes you will. Yes you did. üôèüèΩ

What‚Äôs a proper warmup up look like: 

1) 5-8 min of low to moderate intensity cardio increasing intensity over time. (EX: treadmill walk, start at incline 2% and increase by 1% every minute maintaining same brisk walking speed).

2) 3-5min of Dynamic movements/stretches targeting the same joints to be trained in the workout. 

3) 5-8min Movement prep, again mimicking the movements you will be training, under lower loads at full range of motion. Use this time to also do any necessary muscle activation and postural set up.

üå¨Dehydration is stressing your body out...

If you have ever sat at your desk, everything feeling fine, just doin your thing and you start to feel your heart racing. Maybe not too much, you just notice it, but then you ignore it and keep going about your day.

Then 6 pm comes around and you realize you drank coffee all day, or maybe just one glass of water üòÆ we‚Äôve all been there üôãüèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è okayyyy.

But, we are literally just unnecessarily stressing ourselves out because we‚Äôre making our body work harder to just keep us alive üôÉ (thanks body btw).

We are adding on stress to a world where we don‚Äôt need to be adding any more...

This is one of those small changes, you make today and you feel better tomorrow! That‚Äôs it.

üí¶You don‚Äôt need to keep the gallon jug at your desk like the bodybuilders like to tell you, just shoot for about 2.5 liters a day.

When you‚Äôre not getting enough water your body increases your heart rate, increases the production of your stress hormone cortisol, and this is where studies have linked anxiety, depression, confusion, and fatigue with dehydration...

Drink up! üíß
